{
  "text": "Age and sex were based on self-report. Education was based on self-report and dichotomized into high school or less versus more than high school, similar to other large population-based studies in young adults [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] ). Of socioeconomic markers (i.e., education, income, and occupation), education is found to be most robustly associated with a variety of mental and physical health outcomes. For this reason, education is often the standard socioeconomic proxy used in epidemiological studies [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] including in young adults [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] and in eating disorders [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] .",
  "correct_citation": {
